<P>WHOEVER &s;hall think fit, to &s;end an Ac|count of what they know, of the Good or Bad Con&s;equences (that equal Ju&s;tice may be done the &s;ame,) from the taking of the&s;e Medicines; by a Letter directed for the AUTHOR, to be left at Mr. JOHN CLARKE's, Book&s;eller, under the <HI>Royal Exchange,</HI> the Favour will be acknowledged; and provided the Facts are truly &s;tated, with the Pati|ents Names, and Places of Re&s;idence, at lea&s;t pri|vate Allowance for any diffident Per&s;on to &s;atisfy them&s;elves of the Truth of &s;uch Facts; the Per&s;ons Name who &s;ends &s;uch Information, &s;hall be made no other U&s;e of, than he him&s;elf gives free Permi&s;|&s;ion.</P>
